TASK: FIX PLAN
The engineer wants a concrete, low-risk plan to implement a fix or change in THIS codebase.
Produce an actionable plan grounded in the evidence: which files to touch, in what order,
how to test it, and how to back it out. Do not write the patch itself — plan it.

REQUEST
{{ question }}
{% if bug_report %}

RELATED BUG / CONTEXT
{{ bug_report }}
{% endif %}
{% if stack_trace %}

STACK TRACE
```
{{ stack_trace }}
```
{% endif %}

EVIDENCE (numbered; cite with [n])
{{ m.evidence_block(evidence) }}
{% if analysis %}

ANALYST NOTES
{{ analysis }}
{% endif %}
{% if tool_results and tool_results|length > 0 %}

TOOL RESULTS
{% for tr in tool_results %}
- {{ tr.tool }} -> {{ (tr.output if tr.output else (tr.error or "no output")) | oneline }}
{% endfor %}
{% endif %}

{{ m.grounding_rules() }}

PLAN GUIDELINES
- The "answer" field is the plan itself. Structure it clearly, e.g.:
    Approach: one-line strategy.
    Steps: an ordered list of concrete edits, each naming a real file/symbol from the
      evidence and citing [n].
    Tests: how to verify (unit/integration tests to add or run).
    Risks & rollback: what could break and how to revert.
  Use \n for line breaks inside the answer string.
- Touch the smallest surface that solves the problem. Prefer reusing existing helpers
  visible in the evidence over adding new abstractions.
- Reference only files/symbols present in the evidence. If a needed area is missing, say so
  in the plan and add a next_action to retrieve/read it, and lower confidence.
- next_actions: 1-3 concrete follow-ups (e.g. "read file X to confirm signature",
  "run tests in module Y"). May be [].
- confidence: how confident you are the plan is correct and complete: low | medium | high.

{{ m.json_rules() }}

SCHEMA (return exactly this shape):
{
  "answer": "the implementation plan: Approach / Steps / Tests / Risks & rollback, with [n] citations and \\n line breaks",
  "confidence": "low|medium|high",
  "next_actions": [
    {"title": "short imperative title", "detail": "concrete step", "rationale": "why it helps"}
  ]
}
